<subSubSection id="C30FB2903520FFECFF47FF64FAC7FF29" pageId="3" pageNumber="359" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3520FFECFF47FF64FAC7FF29" blockId="3.[151,1437,150,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">
<emphasis id="B9613D093520FFECFF47FF64FD89FF4C" bold="true" box="[199,550,150,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Distribution and Comments.</emphasis>
Known only from its type locality in the Colombian Andes (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3520FFECFA80FF65FAF6FF4D" box="[1280,1369,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 57" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1890,1914]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-22@15.[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 57. Distribution of jumping spiders of the tribe Lapsiini Maddison (Salticidae: Spartaeinae) in South America. The figures with a dot inside represent the type species of each genus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501154/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93520FFECFF17FF49FF56FF29" box="[151,249,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="359">holotype</typeStatus>
male was collected during the day, under a decaying trunk, in a secondary high-Andean moist forest.
</paragraph>
